text.b: Draft EIR for New Academic Center, Kentfield, California

page.text: Project Applicant: Marin Community College District
Notice: Notice is hereby given that the Marin Community College District (District), acting as Lead Agency
under the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA), will receive public comment and recommendations on
a Draft Environmental Impact Report (EIR) prepared for the New Academic Center at College of Marin,
Kentfield Campus. The review period extends for 45 days beginning December 18, 2012 and ends at 5:00 pm on
January 31, 2013. All comments regarding the Draft EIR must be received by this ending date/time.
Project Location: The project site is located on the central campus of the Kentfield Campus, near the corner of
College Avenue and Sir Francis Drake Boulevard.
The proposed New Academic Center (NAC) would have a gross floor area
44,257 square feet excluding the atrium. The building would be three levels with a final building height of two
stories (28 feet) on the College Avenue frontage and also two stories (26 feet) on the main campus level. The
first floor level of the new building would include space for 8 classrooms, including 2 computer labs and an
English as a Second Language (ESL) lab, and a study room, ESL office and workroom mechanical, electrical
and IT rooms. The second level on the main campus level would include 12 classrooms, including a large
120-seat capacity lecture classroom, 15 offices (including offices for the President and Vice-President of the
College), 2 large conference rooms and 2 small conference rooms, reception area, an adjunct office suite that
could be used for part-time faculty, ancillary rooms such as break room, storage room, and file rooms. The upper
level of the building would include 27 offices for faculty and administrative assistants, the Dean’s office, and a
large conference room, workroom and copy room. Restroom facilities, IT closets and custodial closets would be
provided on each floor. The NAC would replace four existing older buildings on the same site as follows: Harlan
Center, Business Management Center, Onley Hall and the Administrative Center. The project would also remove
the Taqueria restaurant on the corner of Sir Francis Drake Boulevard and College Avenue. The Austin Science
Center, which was originally proposed to be demolished, would be potentially retained. This building is not on or
near the NAC site, but its retention is evaluated as part of the cumulative impact analysis.
Potential Environmental Impacts: No significant, unavoidable impacts have been identified. Some potentially
significant impacts were identified related to aesthetics, air quality, noise, transportation, and public
services/utilities. Each of these impacts would be mitigated to a less than significant level if the identified
mitigation measures are implemented. The District has agreed to implementation of the mitigation measures;
therefore, impacts will be less than significant.

The proposed New Academic Center (NAC) would have a gross floor area of 44,257 square feet
excluding the atrium. The building would be three levels with a final building height of two
stories (28 feet) on the College Avenue frontage and also two stories (26 feet) on the main
campus level. The first floor level of the new building would include space for 8 classrooms,
including 2 computer labs and an English as a Second Language (ESL) lab, and a study room,
ESL office and workroom mechanical, electrical and IT rooms. The second level on the main
campus level would include 12 classrooms, including a large 120-seat capacity lecture classroom,
15 offices (including offices for the President and Vice-President of the College), 2 large
conference rooms and 2 small conference rooms, reception area, an adjunct office suite that could
be used for part-time faculty, ancillary rooms such as break room, storage room, and file rooms.
The upper level of the building would include 27 offices for faculty and administrative assistants,
the Dean’s office, and a large conference room, workroom and copy room. Restroom facilities, IT
closets and custodial closets would be provided on each floor.
The NAC would replace four existing older buildings on the same site as follows: Harlan Center,
Business Management Center, Onley Hall and the Administrative Center. The project would also
remove the Taqueria restaurant on the corner of Sir Francis Drake Boulevard and College
Avenue. The Austin Science Center, which was originally proposed to be demolished, would be
potentially retained. This building is not on or near the NAC site, but its retention is evaluated as
part of the cumulative impact analysis.
The new building would be located in a high elevation portion of the campus at the intersection of
Sir Francis Drake Boulevard and College Avenue. The new project would connect via piping to
the existing geothermal field and Central Plant which is housed in the new Math Science Central
Plant project (under construction) for the project’s heating and cooling needs.
The Marin Community College District, as lead agency, determined that preparation of an
Environmental Impact Report (EIR) was necessary for the project because there was “substantial
evidence that the proposed project may have a significant effect on the environment” for specific
topic areas. An Initial Study Checklist was prepared and circulated from August 31, 2012 to
October 1, 2012. The Checklist identified the issues that would be the focus of the EIR (see
Appendix C). The California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) requires that, before a project
with potentially significant environmental effects may be approved, an EIR must be prepared
that fully describes the environmental effects of the project, identifies mitigation measures to

lessen or eliminate adverse impacts, and examines feasible alternatives to the project. The
information contained in the EIR is to be reviewed and considered by the lead agency prior to
the ultimate decision to approve, disapprove, or modify the proposed project.

This EIR has been prepared by the Marin Community College District, as lead agency, in
conformance with CEQA. This EIR is intended to provide the information and environmental
analyses necessary to assist the public’s understanding of the project and its likely
environmental consequences, and to assist public agency decision-makers in considering the
approvals necessary to implement the proposed project. The proposed project is described to a
sufficient level of detail in Chapter 3 of this document to identify and evaluate any associated
The following provisions of the guidelines for implementing CEQA (known as the “CEQA
Guidelines”) help define the role of this EIR:
CEQA Guidelines §15121(a): Informational Document. An EIR is an
informational document which will inform public agency decision-makers and the
public generally of the significant environmental effect(s) of a project, identify
possible ways to minimize the significant effects, and describe reasonable
alternatives to the project. The public agency shall consider the information in the
EIR along with other information, which may be presented to the agency.
CEQA Guidelines §15151: Standards for Adequacy of an EIR. An EIR should
be prepared with a sufficient degree of analysis to provide decision-makers with
information which enables them to make a decision which intelligently takes
account of environmental consequences. An evaluation of the environmental
College of Marin New Academic Center
effects of a proposed project need not be exhaustive, but the sufficiency of an
EIR is to be reviewed in the light of what is reasonably feasible. Disagreement
among experts does not make an EIR inadequate, but the EIR should summarize the
main points of disagreement among the experts. The courts have looked not for
perfection but for adequacy, completeness, and a good faith effort at full
Further, CEQA states that the lead agency should not “approve projects as proposed if there are
feasible alternatives or feasible mitigation measures available which would substantially lessen the
significant environmental effects of such projects…” (PRC § 21002). If the lead agency
approves the project despite residual significant adverse impacts that cannot be mitigated to less-
than-significant levels, the agency must adopt a “Statement of Overriding Considerations” stating
the reasons for its action in writing.
CEQA Guidelines § 15382 defines a significant effect on the environment as “a substantial, or
potentially substantial, adverse change in any of the physical conditions within the area affected by
the project…” Therefore, in identifying the significant impacts of the project, this EIR
concentrates on the project’s substantial physical effects and on mitigation measures to avoid,
reduce, or otherwise alleviate those effects.
CEQA requires that an EIR discuss a reasonable range of alternatives to the proposed project. This
EIR describes and analyzes a reasonable range of alternatives, including a “No Project” alternative
as required under CEQA (CEQA Guidelines § 15126.6[e]). Chapter 5 of this document
discusses the environmental effects of each alternative, compares the environmental effects of
each alternative with the environmental setting and with the effects of the project and each other
alternative, and addresses the relationship of each alternative to the project objectives. The
determinations of the lead agency concerning the feasibility, acceptance, or rejection of each and
all alternatives considered in this EIR will be addressed and resolved in the District’s findings,
when the Marin Community College District considers approval of the project, as required by
Under CEQA, the environmental baseline for a proposed project analyzed in an EIR is typically
the physical environmental conditions that exist in the vicinity of the project at the time the
Notice of Preparation (NOP) is published (see Appendix A). The NOP for this project was
published on August 31, 2012, and this is the date assumed for the “baseline” conditions against
which the environmental impacts of the proposed project will be analyzed.

College of Marin New Academic Center
The proposed NAC would have a gross floor area of 44,257 square feet excluding the atrium. The
building would be three levels with a final building height of two stories (28 feet) on the College
Avenue frontage and also two stories (26 feet) on the main campus level. The first floor level of
the new building would include space for 8 classrooms, including 2 computer labs and an English
as a Second Language (ESL) lab, and a study room, ESL office and workroom mechanical,
electrical and IT rooms. The second level on the main campus level would include 12 classrooms,
including a large 120-seat capacity lecture classroom, 15 offices (including offices for the
President and Vice-President of the College), 2 large conference rooms and 2 small conference
rooms, reception area, an adjunct office suite that could be used for part-time faculty, ancillary
rooms such as break room, storage room, and file rooms. The upper level of the building would
include 27 offices for faculty and administrative assistants, the Dean’s office, and a large
conference room, workroom and copy room. Restroom facilities, IT closets and custodial closets
would be provided on each floor.
The existing Administrative Center, Business Management Center, Olney Hall and Harlan Center
would be demolished because the cost of repairing these buildings and bringing them up to
current building standards would be far greater than replacing the buildings altogether. The
timing of demolition is dependent upon the construction schedule, but would occur prior to the
beginning of any construction associated with the NAC. It is estimated that demolition may begin
late spring of 2013. The demolition of campus buildings was addressed in the 2007 Program EIR
prepared for the Bond Spending Implementation Plan for the Kentfield campus that was certified
in November 2007 and therefore is not addressed herein (Marin Community College District,
2007). At that time it was proposed that the Austin Science Center be demolished. This EIR
evaluates the possible retention of the Austin Science Center as related to potential cumulative
impacts, as the District is now considering retaining this campus building. Detailed assessments
were done by a team of engineers, architects, and specialists in hazards, ventilation, and other
specialties during 2006 (Marin Community College District, 2006c). Full copies of these
assessments can be viewed at the offices of Swinerton Management & Consulting located on the
Kentfield campus, Trailer PV 8 at Parking Lot No. 12, and on the College’s website.

The Marin Community College District is committed to upgrading the College’s facilities in
compliance with the Measure C Bond Program. The following objectives have been identified for
the overall Implementation Plan and also apply to the specific currently proposed projects:
Provide functional instructional and administrative space to meet program requirements;
Provide upgrades to the existing Kentfield campus to serve the population in this area;
Provide job training and academic programs to assist the unemployed and underemployed
Provide lower division college classes for transfer students to 4-year university programs;
Participate in a collaborative partnership with other educational providers, the business
community, and local government to better serve the community;
Improve campus facilities to accommodate a total campus population of approximately
6,400 students at completion of the Bond Spending Implementation Plan;
Focus development within the existing central area of the Kentfield campus;
Meet LEED criteria (even if formal certification is not obtained);
Modernize classrooms, laboratories, and libraries to meet contemporary standards of
Implement modern computer technology for the campus;
Upgrade buildings for fire safety, energy conservation, seismic safety, and campus security;
Implement “green building” practices in all capital improvement projects; and
Locate the New Academic Center in such a way that valuable campus open space is not
compromised and the “Central Green” is maintained.

The EIR analyses identified no significant unavoidable impacts.
Alternatives to the proposed project are addressed in detail in Chapter 5 of the EIR and are
No Project Alternative: Under this alternative, the construction of the NAC would not
occur. The Administrative Center, Business Management Center, Olney Hall and Harlan
Center would be retained. However, as discussed in the 2007 Program EIR, the cost of
repairing these buildings and bringing them up to current building standards would be far
greater than replacing the buildings altogether. Thus, retention of these buildings could
create a public safety risk due to the buildings’ condition and the result would not meet
program needs for the project. The Taqueria restaurant and associated parking would
remain at the corner of College Avenue and Sir Francis Drake Boulevard and the Austin
Science Center would be retained under this alternative.
Smaller Footprint Alternative: This alternative assumes a smaller footprint for the NAC
to mitigate potential visual impacts along College Avenue. The removal of the four onsite
buildings would still occur. The design of the building, other than along College Avenue,
would remain unchanged. Along College Avenue, a portion of the first and second floor
would be removed to “visually divide” this frontage and to reduce the long façade along
College Avenue. Otherwise, the basic footprint would remain unchanged. The Austin
Science Center would be retained under this alternative.

College of Marin New Academic Center
The Marin Community College District Board of Trustees, hereinafter referred to as the Trustees,
will serve as the lead agency for the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) document for
the proposed New Academic Center (referred to herein as “NAC”) proposed on the Kentfield
campus of the College of Marin.
The NAC was addressed in the Program Environmental Impact Report (Program EIR) completed
for the Bond Spending Implementation Plan (hereinafter also referred to as the Implementation
Plan) for the Kentfield campus that was certified on November 7, 2007 (Marin Community
College District, 2007). The Implementation Plan is the outcome of and the guiding document for
the Measure C Bond Program that was passed by the Marin County voters in 2004. This bond
program provided $249.5 million to be used for modernization and new construction at the
District’s campuses – the Kentfield campus and the Indian Valley campus.
A Program EIR was prepared to address overall changes on the Kentfield campus because
specific details about some of the proposed buildings were not yet available at the time of the
Program EIR, including details about the NAC. It was understood that further environmental
review might be necessary when such details were known. Now, floor plans and detailed plans
have been developed for the NAC addressed herein. The Trustees will be responsible for adopting
a Focused EIR certifying that the proposed project meets all the requirements of the CEQA. After
the certification of the Final EIR for the NAC, the new project can be approved. Construction
would also require the prior approval of the Division of the State Architect (DSA).
Detailed floor plans and other drawings can be reviewed at the Swinerton Management &
Consulting Offices, Trailer PV8, Parking Lot No. 12 of the Kentfield campus. The 2007 Program
EIR and other associated documents can be viewed on the College’s website
Bond Spending Implementation Plan for College of Marin: Kentfield Campus (2007-2013) is
The Kentfield campus is located in central Marin County in the unincorporated community of
Kentfield. The main access to the 87-acre campus is provided via Sir Francis Drake Boulevard
College of Marin New Academic Center
and College Avenue. Other roads abutting the campus include Laurel Avenue and Kent Avenue.
A regional and project location map is provided in Figure 3-1.
Major highway access to the project site is available from U.S. Highway 101, about 2 miles east
of the campus. Sir Francis Drake Boulevard is a main exit from this highway for those coming
from the north, south, and east. For those coming from west Marin County, the main access to the
campus is from Sir Francis Drake Boulevard, which provides access to San Anselmo, Fairfax,
Point Reyes, Inverness, and other communities to the west.
The Kentfield campus (see Figure 3-1) includes about 13 acres which are developed as the
“main” campus where most of the academic buildings are concentrated and where the proposed
NAC would be located. Corte Madera Creek has been channelized in a concrete channel and
forms the southern boundary of the main campus (see Figure 3-1). Two bridges currently provide
both pedestrian and emergency vehicle access across the creek to the main campus.
The NAC would replace four existing older buildings on the same site as follows: Harlan Center,
Business Management Center, Onley Hall and the Administrative Center. The project would also
remove the Taquiera restaurant on the corner of Sir Francis Drake Boulevard and College
Avenue. A site plan for the NAC is shown in Figure 3-2. The proposed NAC would be a new
building located near the intersection of Sir Francis Drake Boulevard and College Avenue.
Elevation in this area of the campus ranges from about 14 feet above mean sea level (msl) to
32 feet above msl. The topographic variation for the project site is approximately 15 feet. The
estimated area of disturbance for the project is approximately three acres. New piping would
connect to the existing geothermal field and Central Plant which is housed in the new Math
Science Central Plant project (under construction) for the NAC’s heating and cooling needs.
The District has undertaken a number of studies to evaluate the existing condition of buildings at
the Kentfield campus. The first study was the “Facility Condition Assessment Report” undertaken
in 2003 by 3D/I (3D/I, 2003). This report formed the basis of the requested improvements for the
Measure C Bond Program that was approved by the County’s voters in 2004. Many of the
Kentfield campus buildings are in a state of disrepair and two are seismically unsafe. The
proposed project responds to the seismic and other conditions related to existing buildings.
The Austin Science Center (51,236 square feet) in the vicinity of Parking Lot 6 was originally
planned for removal as part of the Implementation Plan. This Center is now proposed to be
potentially retained and to be used for general education classrooms. The Austin Science Center
includes 18 lecture classrooms (648-person capacity), 1 large lecture class (108-person capacity),
2 computer labs (125-person capacity), offices, conference rooms, a storage and maintenance
rooms. The total person capacity of the Austin Science Center is approximately 975 persons.

The student population is not expected to change as a result of retaining Austin Science Center.
The building would be retained due to the educational functionality of its teaching spaces, not for
growth purposes. The building is located within the 100-year floodplain. Garage parking forms
the ground level of the building and classrooms are elevated. The location of the Austin Science
Center in the 100-year floodplain is an existing condition and thus no new impacts would be
created as related to hydrological conditions. This CEQA evaluation will address both the NAC
and the retention of the Austin Science Center.
At completion of the entire Implementation Plan (estimated to be 2016), the campus is expected
to have an enrollment of about 6,400 students, which is about a four percent increase (one percent
per year) over the 2011-2012 enrollment (6,184 students). The retention of the Austin Science
Center is not expected to alter this estimated enrollment which is unchanged from what was
assumed in the Program EIR. As such, the proposed NAC and retention of the Austin Science
Center would have no growth-inducing impacts for the campus. The Implementation Plan would
now provide for a net addition in building square footage of 8,000 to 11,000 gross square feet
(gsf) on the Kentfield campus. The Implementation Plan originally estimated a reduction of
square footage of 40,000 to 45,000 gsf, as Austin Science Center was assumed to be removed.
The proposed NAC would have a gross floor area of 44,257 square feet excluding the atrium. The
2007 Program EIR assumed a similar square footage (48,000 gsf) and a building height of two
The building would be three levels with a final building height of two stories (28 feet) on
the College Avenue frontage and also two stories (26 feet) on the main campus level. The first
floor level of the new building would include space for 8 classrooms, including 2 computer labs
and an English as a Second Language (ESL) lab, and a study room, ESL office and workroom
mechanical, electrical and IT rooms. The second level on the main campus level would include
12 classrooms, including a large 120-seat capacity lecture classroom, 15 offices (including offices
for the President and Vice-President of the College), 2 large conference rooms and 2 small
conference rooms, reception area, an adjunct office suite that could be used for part-time faculty,
ancillary rooms such as break room, storage room, and file rooms. The upper level of the building
would include 27 offices for faculty and administrative assistants, the Dean’s office, and a large
conference room, workroom and copy room. Restroom facilities, IT closets and custodial closets
would be provided on each floor. Figures 3-3 through 3-6 provide a bird’s eye view of the project
and an artist’s rendering of the proposed project.
The 48,000 square foot NAC was addressed as Alternative 4 in the Program EIR for the Implementation Plan and
this alternative was selected by the Marin Community College Board of Trustees.

This Draft EIR has been prepared in accordance with CEQA, as amended (Public Resources

This chapter contains the analysis of the potential effects on the environment considered under
CEQA, from development of the proposed New Academic Center (NAC) on the Kentfield
campus of the College of Marin. This chapter describes the existing setting for each topic, the
potential impacts that could result from the construction and operation of the NAC, and relevant
plans and policies that would minimize or avoid potential adverse environmental impacts that
could result. Finally, this chapter identifies mitigation measures necessary to reduce the potential
impacts resulting from the proposed project.
The following provides an overview of the scope of the analysis included in this chapter,
organization of the sections and, the methods for determining significant impacts.
The following sections in this chapter analyze the environmental topics as listed below and
presented in the Table of Contents at the front of this document:
The remaining topics outlined in Appendix G of the CEQA Guidelines were determined to have a
less than significant impact on the environment in the Initial Study, and are not further discussed
in this EIR. The Initial Study is presented in Appendix C of this EIR.

This EIR identifies all impacts with an alpha designation that corresponds to the environmental
topic addressed in each section (e.g., “NOISE” for Section 4.D, Noise). The topic designator is
followed by a number that indicates the sequence in which the impact statement occurs within the
section. For example, “Impact NOISE-1” is the first (i.e., “1”) noise impact identified in the EIR.
All impact statements are presented in bold text.
The Impact Classification of the project’s effects prior to implementation of mitigation measures
is stated in parentheses immediately following the impact statement.
Similarly, each mitigation measure is numbered to correspond with the impact that it addresses.
Where multiple mitigation measures address a single impact, each mitigation measure is
numbered sequentially. For example “Mitigation Measure NOISE-1” is the first mitigation
identified to address the first noise impact (i.e., “NOISE-1”).
Beyond the mitigation measures identified in this EIR, mitigation measures applicable to the
proposed project as identified in the 2007 Program EIR are shown in Appendix H.
The CEQA Guidelines § 15382 defines a significant effect on the environment as “a substantial,

text.i: or potentially substantial, adverse change in any of the physical conditions within the area
affected by the project, including land, air, water, minerals, flora, fauna, ambient noise, and
objects of historic or aesthetic significance. An economic or social change by itself shall not be
considered a significant effect on the environment. A social or economic change related to a

page.text: physical change may be considered in determining whether the physical change is significant.”
Determinations of significance vary with the physical conditions affected and the setting in which
the change occurs. The significance criteria used in this EIR are the thresholds for determining
significance of potential impacts and are based on Appendix G of the CEQA Guidelines.
The following level of significance classifications are used throughout the impact analysis in this EIR:
Less than Significant (LS) – The impacts of the proposed project do not reach or exceed
the defined Threshold/Criteria of Significance. Generally, no mitigation measure is
Significant (S) – The impact of the proposed project is expected to reach or exceed the
defined Threshold/Criteria of Significance. Feasible mitigation measures are identified to
reduce the significant impact to a less than significant level.
4. Environmental Setting, Impacts, Standard Conditions of Approval and Mitigation Measures
College of Marin New Academic Center
Significant Unavoidable (SU) – The impact of the proposed project reaches or exceeds the
defined Threshold/Criteria of Significance. No feasible mitigation measure is available to
reduce the S impact to LS. In these cases, feasible mitigation measures are identified to
reduce the S impact to the maximum feasible extent, and the significant impact is
considered SU. Impacts are also classified as SU if a feasible mitigation measure is identified
that would reduce the impact to LS, but the approval and/or implementation of the
mitigation measure is not within the District’s sole control, in which case the analysis cannot
presume implementation of the mitigation measure and the resulting LS impact. It is
important to clarify that SU is an impact classification that only applies after consideration
No Impact (N) – No noticeable adverse effect on the environment would occur.

CEQA defines cumulative as “two or more individual effects which, when considered together,
are considerable, or which can compound or increase the other environmental impacts.” CEQA
Guidelines § 15130 requires that an EIR evaluate potential environmental impacts when the
project’s incremental effect is cumulatively considerable. “Cumulatively considerable” means
that the incremental effects of an individual project are significant when viewed in connection
with the effects of past, present, existing, approved, pending and reasonably foreseeable future
projects. These impacts can result from a combination of the proposed project together with other
projects causing related impacts. “The cumulative impact from several projects is the change in the
environment which results from the incremental impact of the project when added to other closely
related past, present, and reasonable foreseeable probable future projects.” The analysis approach
for this EIR included “past, present, existing, approved, pending and reasonably foreseeable
The context used for assessing cumulative impacts typically varies depending on the specific

Parks and open space areas are scattered throughout the area, with the most dominant ones in the
nearby vicinity being the larger Mount Tamalpais State Park about 3.5 miles to the southwest of
the main campus and the Hal Brown Park at Creekside, a local park of 26 acres east of the project
site. The terrain is variable with large expanses of level topography interspersed with many low-
lying hillsides. Views from roadways that can be constrained by hillsides in one area open up to
long-distance vistas when the terrain becomes more level. Mount Tamalpais (elevation of
2,574 feet above mean sea level) forms the dominant visual feature from many locations in this
portion of Marin County as well as from many campus locations.
The NAC project site is located at the northeastern corner of the College of Marin Kentfield
campus immediately adjacent to College Avenue. The project site is bounded by College Avenue
to the east, Sir Francis Drake Boulevard to the north, the campus Learning Resources Center to
the south, and the “Central Green” to the west. As shown in Figure 4.A-1a, the site as viewed
along College Avenue is a combination of existing buildings and native and non-native mature
trees that screen Olney Hall and the Administrative Center from view. The main built element
visible for northbound motorists at this location on College Avenue is the arched entry over the
Olney Hall entrance. The mature trees include a mixture of deciduous and evergreen trees with
trunk diameters ranging from 8 inches to 24 inches (as measured at breast height) (RHAA, 2012).
The existing trees along the College Avenue frontage of the project site include the following:
four Pinus canariensis, one Pinus radiata, one Quercus agrifolia, one Fraxinus ornus, two
Leptospermum laevigatum (multi-trunked), one Magnolia denudata, one Fraxinus holotricha, and
one Juniperus chinensis ‘Torulosa’. From farther south on College Avenue, additional street trees
provide even more screening of the project site (see Figure 4.A-1b) as street trees are located
close to the Corte Madera Creek crossing. In both images, the Kentfield Fire Department building
is visible in the background (right side of image).

4. Environmental Setting, Impacts and Mitigation Measures
College of Marin New Academic Center
The other main portion of the site where significant tree cover is visible from locations off the site
includes the corner of College Avenue and Sir Francis Drake Boulevard. Currently, this corner is
occupied by the Taqueria restaurant and about 17 parking spaces that serve the restaurant. Four
large redwoods (Sequoia sempervirens) ranging in trunk diameter from 12 inches to 24 inches are
planted at the edge of the sidewalk in this location (see Figure 4.A-2a).
A grove of about 13 redwood trees is located to the west and northwest of the Taqueria restaurant,
north of Harlan Center (see Figure 4.A-2b). The existing tree canopy forms the major visual
element of this corner of the site as seen by passing motorists on Sir Francis Drake Boulevard.
Within the more central portions of the site and surrounding the Business Center, mature trees
include a mixture of oaks, Japanese maples, magnolias, liquidambars, and maytens.
The project site is currently occupied by Olney Hall, the Administrative Center, the Business Center,
Harlan Center, and the Taqueria Restaurant. All of these buildings would be removed to allow
construction of the proposed project. These existing buildings are separated by small landscaped areas
which include pathways, stairs, turf areas, and mature trees. The architectural style of many of the
existing buildings on the project site is “Mission revival” style, with distinguishing features being
the red tile roofs, cement plaster siding, exterior arcades, exposed rafters, and operable windows.
The Administrative Center also includes historically-significant architectural features such as
arcade columns with concrete cast ornamentation.
Harlan Center is a two-story building that is
most visible from interior portions of the campus and that does not include the Mission revival
style elements found in many of the other onsite buildings. This building includes brick siding
and shingle roofing as shown in Figure 4.A-3a and 4.A-3b. A large beech tree located northwest
of Harlan Center screens much of the building from view as seen from Sir Francis Drake
From Maple Avenue, which intersects Sir Francis Drake
Boulvard, Harlan Center is not screened by the beech tree.
The site varies in topography with the lower portions of the site along College Avenue and
adjacent to Sir Francis Drake Boulevard, and the upper portions of the site farther to the west
adjacent to the “Central Green”. A series of stairways provides pedestrian access to the upper
portions of the site. No parking is provided on the site and the nearest parking is adjacent to
College Avenue at the southeast corner of the Learning Resources Center.
The historic features of the Administrative Center were addressed in the 2007 Program EIR completed for the Bond
Spending Implementation Plan for the Kentfield campus, and mitigation measures were identified and adopted for
the impacts due to proposed demolition (Marin Community College District, 2007).
The large beech tree is outside the limit of work and would be retained.

4. Environmental Setting, Impacts and Mitigation Measures
College of Marin New Academic Center
Primary public views of the site occur from College Avenue and Sir Francis Drake Boulevard, from
the adjacent commercial uses on the east sides of College Avenue, from a few residences on Sir
Francis Drake Boulevard, and from nearby uphill residential areas. Views of the project site vary
depending on the vantage point and the distance from the site. In general, views from College
Avenue are primarily of the frontage tree cover along the perimeter of the site (see Figure 4.A-1a
and 4.A-1b). Mt. Tamalpais is visible in the background of some of the views along College
Avenue but is partially screened by the large existing trees along College Avenue. From Sir
Francis Drake Boulevard, much of the site is screened by existing mature trees such as the grove
of redwoods and the large beech tree near Harlan Center (see Figures 4.A-2, 3 and 4). Views of
Mt. Tamalpais are most prominent near the northwestern portion of the site, where one can look
from Sir Francis Drake Boulevard towards the mountain, with the existing Harlan Center at the
left of this image and the lawn by Circle Drive in the foreground (see Figure 4.A-4).
Mt. Tamalpais is also visible above the rooftops of the onsite buildings for southbound motorists
and pedestrians on College Avenue, but this view is partially screened by intervening trees and
